post_cb({"bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_12903294_12903307_1": {"length": 18, "quality": 0.8571428571428571, "section_id": 5313}, "so_12903294_12903307_0": {"length": 27, "quality": 0.9, "section_id": 5313}}, "n3337": {"so_12903294_12903307_1": {"length": 18, "quality": 0.8571428571428571, "section_id": 5110}, "so_12903294_12903307_0": {"length": 27, "quality": 0.9, "section_id": 5110}}, "n4659": {"so_12903294_12903307_1": {"length": 18, "quality": 0.8571428571428571, "section_id": 6737}, "so_12903294_12903307_0": {"length": 27, "quality": 0.9, "section_id": 6737}}}, "12903304": {"Id": "12903304", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p><code>\\</code> escapes the newline. <code>g++</code> will read <code>if(x==y){</code> on one line, which is not a syntax error.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2012-10-15T20:16:36.347", "Score": "6", "CreationDate": "2012-10-15T20:16:36.347", "ParentId": "12903294", "CommentCount": "0", "OwnerUserId": "1173513"}, "12903294": {"ViewCount": "312", "Body": "<p>This code will work and run fine with g++.\nI do not no why. It should give an error.</p>\n<pre><code>#include &lt;iostream&gt;\nusing namespace std;\nint main(){\n    int x=9;\n    int y=6;\n    //note that there is extra backslash in the end of if statement\n    if(x==y)\\\n    {\n        cout&lt;&lt;\"x=y\"&lt;&lt;endl;\n    }\n    //note that there is extra backslash in the end of if statement\n    if(x!=y)\\\n    {\n        cout&lt;&lt;\"x!=y\"&lt;&lt;endl;\n    }\n    return 0;\n}\n</code></pre>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "12903307", "Title": "An extra backslash character do not effect my program. Why?", "CreationDate": "2012-10-15T20:15:42.810", "Id": "12903294", "CommentCount": "1", "LastEditDate": "2016-06-07T14:53:57.283", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "3865653", "LastActivityDate": "2016-06-07T14:53:57.283", "Score": "5", "OwnerUserId": "1061392", "Tags": "<c++><gcc><g++><backslash>", "AnswerCount": "2"}, "12903307": {"Id": "12903307", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>From the C++ Standard:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_12903294_12903307_0\">(C++11, 2.2p1) \"Each instance of a backslash character (\\) immediately followed by a new-line character is deleted, splicing physical source lines to form logical source lines. Only the last backslash on any physical source line shall be eligible for being part of such a splice.\"</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>C says exactly the same:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_12903294_12903307_1\">(C11, 5.1.1.2 Translatation phases p1) \"Each instance of a backslash character (\\) immediately followed by a new-line character is deleted, splicing physical\n  source lines to form logical source lines.\"</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>So:</p>\n<pre><code>if(x==y)\\\n{\n    cout&lt;&lt;\"x=y\"&lt;&lt;endl;\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>is actually equivalent to:</p>\n<pre><code>if(x==y){\n    cout&lt;&lt;\"x=y\"&lt;&lt;endl;\n}\n</code></pre>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2012-10-15T20:16:45.037", "Score": "19", "CreationDate": "2012-10-15T20:16:45.037", "ParentId": "12903294", "CommentCount": "4", "OwnerUserId": "1119701"}});